a textual world in which scriptural reading was multisensory and multitraditional. As they addressed sickness, demonic struggle, and interpersonal conflicts, Mediterranean people thus acted in ways that challenge our conceptual boundaries between Christians and non-Christians; elites and non-elites; and words, materials, and images. Sanzo helps us rethink how early Christians imagined similarity and difference among texts, traditions, groups, and rituals as they went about their daily lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 7aRELIGION / Antiquities & Archaeology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079135840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520399198zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520399198/original  a978-3-11-079135-8  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA